<!DOCTYPE assessment PUBLIC "-//Carnegie Mellon University//DTD Inline Assessment MathML 1.4//EN" "http://oli.cmu.edu/dtd/oli_inline_assessment_mathml_1_4.dtd"><assessment xmlns:cmd="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/content/metadata/2.1/" id="identify_erythrocytes_leukocytes_thrombocytes_digt_02"><title>tutor</title><page id="ab801c1f22134c639789abba8dab6aa5"><title>Assessment Page Title</title><question id="q1"><body><p id="aadd7e1718b07494595dfa6473bcdbd27">Which type of blood cell contains the greatest amount of iron?</p></body><multiple_choice id="a35257945fef46738c5f56ef711320f3" labels="false" select="single" shuffle="true"><choice value="choice1">red blood cells</choice><choice value="choice2">granulocytes</choice><choice value="choice3">agranulocytes</choice><choice value="choice4">leukocytes</choice></multiple_choice><part id="q1_p1"><skillref idref="compare_features_erythrocytes_leukocytes_SKILL" /><response match="choice1" score="10"><feedback><p id="ad02df96b6bdc420a8941a4e8e562caa1">Correct. Red blood cells contain 4 iron atoms in each hemoglobin molecule, and they have hundreds of millions of hemoglobin molecules.</p></feedback></response><response match="choice2" score="0"><feedback><p id="ae0a615ea698e46e6b023c27cd76c5c73">Incorrect. Granulocytes are distinguished by the presence of granules not iron.</p></feedback></response><response match="choice3" score="0"><feedback><p id="acb0c3f8de169415188ccfb0371049e79">Incorrect. Agranulocytes are a type of white blood cell that do not contain as much iron as another choice.</p></feedback></response><response match="choice4" score="0"><feedback><p id="ae810850f301e42d78af57fe9c0814c6a">Incorrect. Leukyocytes are white blood cells that are characterized by possessing granules or not possessing granules, but not for containing iron.</p></feedback></response></part></question><question id="q2"><body><p id="ae521a842617b466285db4f2bd094fecb">Which of the following do not have nuclei?</p></body><multiple_choice id="d8837c0ab70948f28224f7c4daeba08b" labels="false" select="single" shuffle="false"><choice value="choice1">red blood cells</choice><choice value="choice2">neutrophils (a type of granulocyte)</choice><choice value="choice3">platelets</choice><choice value="choice4">lymphocytes (a type of agranulocyte)</choice><choice value="choice5">red blood cells and platelets</choice><choice value="choice6">neutrophils and lymphocytes (both are types of leukocytes)</choice></multiple_choice><part id="q2_p1"><skillref idref="identify_micro_erythrocytes_leukocytes_thrombocytes_SKILL" /><response match="choice1" score="0"><feedback><p id="adb2faabd7cb34ac1914c247318898ec4">Incorrect. Although true that red blood cells do not have nuclei, they are not the only choice that lacks a nucleus.</p></feedback></response><response match="choice2" score="0"><feedback><p id="afcaa6311f3f545f1902541168f68d827">Incorrect. Neutrophils have large, multi-lobed nuclei.</p></feedback></response><response match="choice3" score="0"><feedback><p id="aadf0c0be412d4c17af07934e1c2d0355">Incorrect. Although platelets lack nuclei, they are not the only choice that lacks a nucleus.</p></feedback></response><response match="choice4" score="0"><feedback><p id="aa49306b69f594780b70e23d0011cbefe">Incorrect. Lymphocytes have large nuclei.</p></feedback></response><response match="choice5" score="10"><feedback><p id="ad6f4b38c13704ea08b05094645df5bc6">Correct. Neither red blood cells or platelets have nuclei.</p></feedback></response><response match="choice6" score="0"><feedback><p id="afd220736fc09463b98c86f13e03bb5fa">Incorrect. Both neutrophils and lymphocytes have large nuclei.</p></feedback></response></part></question></page></assessment>
